# Visual Instructional Standard for LeetCode

Visuals are optional by default.
They exist to remove real confusion, not to make a README feel more substantial.

## Placement Rule

Put visuals in `## Appendix`, not in `## Fundamentals`, unless the user explicitly asks for a visually-led note.

## Quantity Rule

- For most problems, `0-3` visuals is enough.
- For visualization-heavy canonical problems, `3-6` visuals is the upper range.
- Do not require `10+` visuals.
- Do not use visual count as a quality metric.

## Teaching Rule

Add a visual only when it materially clarifies one of these:
- geometry or physical layout,
- pruning or safe-discard logic,
- state transitions,
- recursion or DP structure,
- invariant preservation,
- or a failure mode that is otherwise hard to explain cleanly.

If a visual merely repeats earlier text or another image, cut it.

## Asset Rule

- Use local `png/` assets for embedded visuals.
- Keep `.dot` sources in `dot/` when the set is nontrivial.
- Use generator code for nontrivial sets.
- Never rely on external hotlinked images for core teaching content.

## Audit Rule

If visuals are present:
- audit every embedded image with `.agents/workflows/visual-image-audit.md`,
- verify the README text around each image matches what it shows,
- and confirm the note remains formally correct even if the visuals are removed.

If no visuals are present, that is not a failure.
